Met with Secretary Rollins, U.S. Forest Service Chief Randy Moore, and Mark Emmerson of Sierra Pacific Industries today to talk about a big investment in wildfire prevention. $75 million is headed to U.S. Forest Service Region 5 for shaded fuel breaks, with $70 million going straight to California. This funding, secured through last year‚Äôs disaster relief legislation, comes at a crucial time as California braces for another tough fire season.

Shaded fuel breaks‚Äîclearing out overgrown vegetation and reducing ground fuels‚Äîare a proven way to slow wildfires and give firefighters a better shot at containment. This funding will get these projects moving across Northern California, helping protect our forests, infrastructure, and the areas most at risk from fast-moving wildfires.

A statesman, inventor, and philosopher, he shaped not just our government, but the very ideals of our nation. As we approach the 250th anniversary of our great nation, it is only right that he be enshrined in the U.S. Capitol to inspire generations to come.
 
That‚Äôs why, alongside my friend and neighbor @RepHoulahan, I‚Äôm proud to lead H.R. 250, the Benjamin Franklin Statue Placement Act. Franklin‚Äôs legacy is a reminder of what is possible when vision and virtue work in concert, and his presence in these halls will stand as an enduring call to leadership, wisdom, and service to the greater good.

Name: Shaheen, Jeanne
text:
üóìÔ∏èFirst, Trump has promised tariffs on our allies, Canada and Mexico‚Äî10% on energy from Canada and 25% on everything else.

Whether they take effect next week or next month, they've already created panic and uncertainty.

Name: Shaheen, Jeanne
text:
How will that effect you? 

For starters, 100,000 jobs across the country would be at risk. Not to mention, raising the cost of new housing construction at a time when we‚Äôre facing a nationwide housing affordability crisis.

Name: Shaheen, Jeanne
text:
Per initial estimates, Trump‚Äôs reciprocal tariffs would:

‚¨ÜÔ∏èRaise costs by $2,700 to $3,400 for households per year

‚¨áÔ∏èShrink the economy by $100 billion per year

With the worst price hikes on everyday items like clothing, electronics, energy and drug prices.

Name: Shaheen, Jeanne
text:
üóìÔ∏èAnd in early April, we can expect Trump to start putting broad reciprocal tariffs on every country we trade with. You heard right‚Äîevery country.

If this happens, tariffs would be at their highest level since the Great Depression.

Name: Shaheen, Jeanne
text:
üóìÔ∏èThen, the next week, Trump plans to level 25% tariffs on steel and aluminum. 

Who uses steel and aluminum? 

Think the auto and aerospace industries, as well as construction companies.

text:
If you guessed prices would rise, you‚Äôre right.

Households can expect to spend an unconscionable $900 to $1,100 more a year on these goods, plus car and drug prices could rise by 8.5% to 10.5%.

text:
You may ask: didn‚Äôt Trump get elected to LOWER costs? How do these actions accomplish that? 

Well, the straightforward answer is: they don‚Äôt.

text:

text:

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we share stories of remarkable individuals whose determination, resilience, and spirit remind us of the power of perseverance. This week, we honor a young man who embodies the heart of a champion‚Äînot just in competition but in life. Meet this week‚Äôs Hometown Hero: Karl Dickersbach of Fairless Hills.
 
At 26 years old, Karl is more than an athlete‚Äîhe is a force of nature. Whether racing through the snow in a blistering 7-minute mile or soaring over the high jump in the summer heat, Karl has proven time and time again that no challenge is too great and no finish line too far. Since joining @SpecialOlympics in elementary school, he has shattered expectations, earning countless medals‚Äîmost of them gold‚Äîcompeting in events like the Rocky Run, the Marine Corps 10K, the Broad Street Run, and the legendary Penn Relays.
 
Through relentless training, unshakable determination, and a belief that there‚Äôs always another level to reach, Karl has proven that resilience is the key to greatness. His coaches struggle to keep up‚Äîeven on a bike‚Äîand his teammates look to him as a leader who elevates everyone around him.
 
Now, Karl is preparing for the biggest race of his life‚Äîrepresenting Pennsylvania at the 2026 Special Olympics USA Games in Minnesota. Among 3,000 elite athletes and 75,000 cheering fans, he will step onto the national stage, the product of years of grit, sacrifice, and determination. And if you ask his coaches‚ÄîTom Delaney and Lisa Rigefsky‚Äîthere‚Äôs no doubt: Karl is bringing home gold.
 
To Coach Delaney, a Bristol Township School District Special Education Life Skills teacher who has spent over 40 years empowering Special Olympics athletes in our community, Coach Rigefsky, and everyone who has supported Karl‚Äôs journey‚Äîwe thank you. Your leadership has helped fuel his success, and now, Karl is ready to make Bucks County proud.
 
Throughout his life, Karl has proven that with courage, heart, and determination, barriers can be broken, expectations surpassed, and limits redefined.
 
Karl, your entire community stands behind you, proud and inspired by your journey. As you prepare to take the national stage, know that we‚Äôll all be cheering for you, our Hometown Hero, every step of the way!

üö® @FinancialCmte Republicans Are Fighting Back Against Biden's Overdraft Rule üö®

The CFPB overstepped its authority with its Biden-Era rule capping overdraft fees. While the rule claims to apply only to large banks, the real impact will hit community banks & consumers hardest.

‚ùå Higher costs for consumers ‚Äì With fewer revenue sources, community banks may be forced to raise account fees, increase minimum balance requirements, or limit low-cost banking options. This could push more Americans out of the banking system, not help them.

‚ùå Unfair market pressure on small banks ‚Äì Large banks may lower their overdraft fees to the CFPB‚Äôs arbitrary $5 benchmark, forcing smaller banks to follow suit or risk losing customers. Unlike big banks, community banks can‚Äôt absorb these losses, leading to reduced services and even bank closures. This rule would lead to consolidation and places community banks at a disadvantage.

‚ùå A blow to financial inclusion ‚Äì Millions of Americans rely on overdraft protection to cover emergency expenses. If banks eliminate or restrict overdraft services, many consumers will have fewer options and be forced toward riskier alternatives.

üö® This rule isn‚Äôt about protecting consumers‚Äîit‚Äôs about scoring cheap political points at the expense of Americans. In reality, it will make banking more expensive and less accessible for working families. If the Biden Administration did their homework and spoke to constituents, they'd know this rule is out of touch.

We have worked to form a more perfect union and tell the story of our past while looking to the future in Greenwood in North Tulsa by adding locations to the National Park Service African-American Civil Rights Network and ensuring the race massacre is taught in all Oklahoma schools. In Oklahoma, we are surrounded by the legacies of trailblazers like Ada Lois Sipuel Fisher, Clara Luper, and many others who left their mark in the law, in classrooms, in the media, and in ministry. We are grateful for all their courage, their leadership, and their example.

text:
As we near the end of Black History Month, I am highlighting the work of Dr. Momodu C. Taylor, Vice President of Institutional Equity at Delaware County Community College. 

Dr. Taylor reflected on his own educational journey, praising his parents as early role models. He also credited his experience at Livingstone College and the teacher education program at North Carolina A&T for showing him the importance of diverse classroom representation. He noted with pride NC A&T's legacy of producing Black professionals and its significant role in the Civil Rights Movement. Dr. Taylor channels his experiences into his current work fostering an inclusive environment at @DelawareCCC, claiming, "the fundamental aspects of teaching remain with me today, along with the purpose that initially motivated me."

Name: Davis, Donald G.
text:
Friday in the First¬†

Dr. Howard Yee has devoted 24 years to caring for the dental needs of his community in Roanoke Rapids, NC, which he has called home for the past 19 years. With each patient encounter, he has made a genuine difference in people‚Äôs lives, enhancing their oral health, confidence, and overall quality of life.

Dr. Yee generously volunteers with organizations such as the Choanoke Area Development Association of NC, Inc., where he provides vital dental screenings for Head Start students. In addition, he selflessly offers free dental services to veterans and uninsured individuals, ensuring that those in need receive the care they deserve. His commitment to service extends beyond his current work; he honorably served in the U.S. Army Reserves from 1989 to 2004, where he was recognized with two U.S. Army Commendation Medals for his courageous contributions during Operation Enduring Freedom and Operation Iraqi Freedom.

Dr. Yee's dedication to helping others is truly inspiring. His volunteer work with the Dental Lifetime Network and NC MOM reflects his unwavering commitment to those in need. Through his career and generous volunteer efforts, Dr. Yee has profoundly changed the lives of countless patients, leaving a heartfelt and lasting impact on his community.

¬†# FridaySpotlight

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Many Democrats are asking what the path forward is, calling for a period of reflection. ‚ÄúWhere did we go wrong? What is the way back?‚Äù¬†Well, how about looking right in front of our own noses.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: For years, creepy billionaires funded (and enjoyed) the destruction of America‚Äôs political money limits, and launched billions in corrupting dark money into American elections. Despite massive public reaction against that, Democrats basically let it happen.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: (In the Senate, we managed two votes in 14 years on the DISCLOSE Act, despite 80/20 polling advantage and massive public response in state referenda.¬†As a result, many voters don‚Äôt know Democrats are any better than Republicans on getting rid of dark money.)

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: For years, creepy billionaires mounted a semi-covert assault to capture and control the Supreme Court, seeking to corrupt the administration of justice in America.¬†Despite massive public hostility to the capture, Democrats barely called it out.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: For years, creepy fossil fuel billionaires ran the largest campaign of corruption and disinformation in American history to propagate climate denial and obstruct climate legislation. Democrats did nearly nothing to expose the campaign as it blockaded us.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: (Biden‚Äôs presidential commission on the Supreme Court tiptoed around this, and he never spoke firmly about the capture effort until his last days in office, when he at last endorsed term limits when it was too late to do anything about it.)

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: (We have been content to pat our own backs over climate legislation that did not create a pathway to climate safety, and bemoan climate change, but never direct public attention at the corrupt climate denial apparatus that is an obvious, culpable villain.)

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: (it went largely unnoticed that the Fed Chair recently predicted that whole regions of the US would be without mortgages after a decade; markets will react before then, so this widely-recognized threat is actually upon us now.¬†Look at Florida.)

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: The creepy billionaire dark money, Court capture and climate denial schemes have put us on the edge of an economic crisis from collapsing property insurance markets, cascading into mortgages, property values and the general economy.¬†Democrats need to get on that.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Want America back? Start with what‚Äôs in front of our noses.¬†Get dark money out of politics. Restore the Court to integrity.¬†Call out fossil fuel lies and end pollute-for-free. The public supports ALL of this.¬†The wind is at our backs, if we‚Äôd only put up our sails.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Is there a theme here?¬†Yes, there is.¬†Creepy right-wing billionaires have infiltrated the government through dark money, captured justices, and a massive political influence armada, creating massive harm, and Democrats have put almost no spotlight on the operation itself.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1872, President Ulysses S. Grant signed a bill establishing Yellowstone as the first national park in the U.S.

Before the Civil War, only a few trappers ventured into Yellowstone. However, it was the 1871 government-led expedition under geologist Ferdinand Hayden that played a crucial role in Yellowstone‚Äôs preservation. Hayden, along with photographer William Jackson and artist Thomas Moran, documented the area‚Äôs beauty, providing visual evidence that captured the attention of Congress.

In 1872, Congress passed the Yellowstone Act, setting aside about 2 million acres across Wyoming, Montana, and Idaho as a national park. This law aimed to preserve Yellowstone‚Äôs natural wonders for public enjoyment and protection from exploitation.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
MAGA is making the claim that if you watch the entire 50 minute video, Zelensky is the antagonist. 

This isn't true. At all. I was with Zelensky before this meeting and it's important to know his mindset heading in.

1/ A short üßµon how the entire ambush went down.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
2/ You cannot erase the context. Trump has been calling Zelensky a corrupt dictator and spreading Russian propaganda that Russia didn't invade Ukraine. 

All these lies are Trump's pretext to sign a deal with Russia that hands Ukraine to Putin. Zelensky knows this.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text: 3/ Zelensky - who's been cut out of the talks - knows what Trump and Putin are scheming. A "ceasefire" without any guarantee for Ukraine's future security is a trap. Trump's deal will require Ukrainian forces to withdraw, and when they do, Putin will pounce. It's a set up.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
4/ So it's true that the first 40 minutes or so of the meeting LOOK cordial. 

But listen to Trump. He keeps repeating that he's going to impose on Zelensky this fake "ceasefire", without any new weapons to Ukraine, without any security guarantee, without any way to enforce it.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
4/ So at the 40 minute mark, Vance chimes in. He appears agitated. He says that Trump's fake "ceasefire" is the only way.

All that happens at this point is that Zelensky asks Vance a simple, calm question. Zelensky isn't being rude. And here's the essence of the question:

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
5/ "Putin has signed many agreements about Ukraine and he hasn't honored any of them. Aren't you worried Putin will violate the terms of this ceasefire?"

That's it. That's the question. 

And this is where Vance and Trump explode. The trap was set and now the ambush starts.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
7/ You've seen the clips that follow. But the whole meeting is a set up. 

By pushing this plan to hand Ukraine to Putin (IN FRONT OF ZELENSKY!), Trump is trying to either humiliate or provoke Zelensky.

But he does neither, and so Vance has to light the match.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
6/ Vance - visibly angry - calls Zelensky "disrespectful" for asking his simple question. And then starts listing Russian talking points about how weak the Ukrainian army is how poor a leader Zelensky is. 

It's Vance that takes a cordial meeting to a hostile one.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
8/ Of course Zelensky had to make his point that Putin won't honor the "ceasefire". He does it diplomatically with a question to Vance (likely so as to not directly confront Trump on TV).

And then Vance see his chance. He commences the ambush.

The whole thing was a set up.

If Liz Cheney were in charge, we‚Äôd likely be on the verge of nuclear world war.

On its own, Ukraine cannot win this war. It‚Äôs outmanned and outgunned by a nation far larger, more wealthy and more powerful than it is.

There are only limited options to proceed. 1) Ukraine can surrender, almost certainly on terms it and the global community find unappealing. 2) The US can prolong the war, costing potentially trillions of dollars, hundreds of thousands of lives, and risking a larger global conflagration with one of the world‚Äôs biggest nuclear superpowers. 3) The US could broker a negotiated peace on acceptable terms, all from a position of strength and global leadership. 

Those are the options, regardless of who started the war or who is a ‚Äúwar criminal.‚Äù

By supporting a negotiated pathway to peace, @realdonaldtrump and @JDVance are making the most out of a bad situation. They‚Äôre saving lives, saving resources and making the world safer.

And they‚Äôre strengthening America‚Äôs role as leader of the free world. Both the American people and the international community should be thankful. 

This is America First leadership in action.

Name: Ogles, Andrew
text: 4/ Historically, judicial review (Marbury v. Madison) belonged to the Supreme Court, not lower courts issuing sweeping injunctions. Justice Thomas, in his Trump v. Hawaii concurrence, called universal injunctions‚Äîused by these judges blocking executive actions‚Äî‚Äúlegally and historically dubious.‚Äù District judges shouldn‚Äôt play SCOTUS, especially when they subvert the American people‚Äôs will.

Name: Ogles, Andrew
text: 2/ The Founders granted the President ‚Äúthe executive Power‚Äù (Art. II, Sec. 1) for decisive action. Hamilton, in Federalist 70, calls ‚Äúenergy in the executive‚Äù the key to good government. Nationwide injunctions from a single district court paralyze that power. That‚Äôs not what the Founders intended.

Name: Ogles, Andrew
text: 3/ Hamilton dubbed the judiciary the ‚Äúleast dangerous‚Äù branch (Federalist 78)‚Äîlacking force or will, it merely judges. However, the judges my colleagues and I are impeaching halt Trump‚Äôs orders nationwide. That‚Äôs not judgment; it‚Äôs unconstitutional overreach masquerading as jurisprudence.

Name: Ogles, Andrew
text: 6/ The Constitution limits judges to serving ‚Äúduring good Behaviour‚Äù (Art. III, Sec. 1). Issuing partisan, nationwide blocks on Trump‚Äôs lawful orders‚Äîrooted in statutes like 8 U.S.C. ¬ß 1182(f)‚Äîisn‚Äôt ‚Äúgood.‚Äù It‚Äôs an abuse of power.

Name: Ogles, Andrew
text: 5/ Take woke Judge Amir Ali, forcing Trump to divert USAID funds to globalist NGOs and illegal aliens. Since when can a district judge override executive discretion on foreign aid? That‚Äôs not adjudication‚Äîit‚Äôs roleplaying commander-in-chief. Madison, in Federalist 51, warned against branches straying from their ‚Äúproper sphere.‚Äù I‚Äôm impeaching Ali for exactly this.

Name: Ogles, Andrew
text: 7/ Hamilton, in Federalist 65, defines ‚ÄúHigh Crimes and Misdemeanors‚Äù for judges as ‚Äúoffenses which proceed from the misconduct of public men‚Ä¶from the abuse or violation of some public trust.‚Äù These acts, he says, are ‚Äúpolitical,‚Äù harming society itself.

Name: Ogles, Andrew
text: 8/ By the way, Congress has the power to regulate federal courts (Art. III, Sec. 2) and impeach (Art. I, Sec. 2). Think of Mayorkas‚Äô impeachment for dereliction of duty at the Southern Border‚Äîthe same principle applies to rogue judges.

Name: Ogles, Andrew
text: 9/ In Trump v. Hawaii (2018), SCOTUS affirmed the President‚Äôs ‚Äúcomprehensive authority‚Äù in national security, rebuking lower courts for overstepping. Yet they persist. Repeated overreach isn‚Äôt independence‚Äîit‚Äôs tyranny.

Name: Ogles, Andrew
text: 10/ Impeachment isn‚Äôt about punishing disagreement‚Äîit‚Äôs about restoring balance. District judges aren‚Äôt elected, but they‚Äôre acting like super-legislators. Congress must defend Trump‚Äôs constitutional duty to execute the law and the people‚Äôs mandate.

Name: Ogles, Andrew
text:
11/ Bottom line: These judges don‚Äôt check power‚Äîthey seize it. Impeach them for bad behavior and abuse of trust. The Founders gave Congress the tools‚Äîuse them. 

End the judicial coup against Trump and oust the lawfare-loving liberals betraying our nation.

Illegal border crossings are now lower than they‚Äôve EVER been recorded. 

After only a few weeks in office, President Trump ended America‚Äôs existential border crisis.

For my entire life, the American people have begged Washington to secure our border. And Presidents from Bill Clinton to George W. Bush to Obama and Biden completely ignored them. They would campaign on securing the border, lie to the American people, and ultimately do nothing.

The lure of millions of new voters or hoards of cheap serf laborers was too appealing to pass up.

But not for Trump.

In February, Border Patrol recorded 8,326 unlawful illegal alien entries.

For reference, when Biden was in office, we‚Äôd have more alien crossings in a single day than that.

8,326 is the lowest number of monthly unlawful entries since Border Patrol began reporting monthly data in 2000.

And while Biden released thousands of unvetted aliens into our heartland every day, the aliens caught under President Trump were detained and deported.

President Trump didn‚Äôt make excuses. He didn‚Äôt focus on ‚Äúroot causes‚Äù or external factors out of our control. He simply chose to enforce America‚Äôs border policies already on the books: capture, detain, deport.

He did his job. 

Thank you, @realDonaldTrump for doing what every past President in modern history said he would do, but didn‚Äôt.

Promises made. Promises kept. America First.

üö® This Week‚Äôs Focus: Potassium Bromate. This banned carcinogen is prohibited in over 30 countries, including the EU, UK, and Canada. Studies have linked potassium bromate to cancer, DNA damage, and kidney disease, yet it remains legal in the U.S. with minimal oversight.

üîé Check labels‚Äîavoid products that contain Potassium Bromate or Bromated Flour.

Name: Roy, Chip
text:
üö® REP. ROY STATEMENT ON INAUGURAL NON-STOP FLIGHT FROM SAN ANTONIO INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT (SAT) TO RONALD REAGAN WASHINGTON NATIONAL AIRPORT (DCA) üö®

‚ÄúThroughout my time in Congress, I have been working side-by-side with my colleagues on both sides of the aisle to find a solution to enable a long overdue nonstop flight between Washington Reagan Airport and San Antonio. ¬†

In April 2023, I led a letter with the San Antonio delegation to build support for this important flight. Additionally, in the Rules Committee on which I serve, we secured a vote on an amendment to add 7 more direct flights to DCA. Though this amendment fell just short in the House, it demonstrated enormous support and helped pave the way for the compromise of 5 additional slots at DCA that we saw in the Senate-passed FAA bill led by Senator Ted Cruz in May 2024.¬†Finally, in July 2024, Senator Ted Cruz and I led a letter to the Department of Transportation (DOT) urging the Biden Administration to award San Antonio with one of the nonstop flight spots.¬†

Today, the people of San Antonio saw the results of the San Antonio delegation's work toward achieving this priority.¬†I am proud to know that the men and women of Military City, U.S.A will finally be able to fly directly to the airport next door to the Pentagon and that all those in the region can visit their nation's capital more easily.

I‚Äôd like to thank Senator Ted Cruz for his steadfast leadership and work on this effort. ¬†I would also like to thank Senator Cornyn, Rep. Henry Cuellar, Rep. Joaquin Castro, Rep. Greg Casar, Rep. Tony Gonzales, and Mayor Nirenberg for banding together to deliver this priority.¬†

Safe travels."

This investment has helped address water security challenges through invasive species management and native species reforestation.

Name: Neal, Richard E.
text:
Mike Slater's story can be summed up in one word: service.

After four tours in Iraq and Afghanistan, he returned home to continue that service, first working as the Director of Veterans' Services for South Hadley, and most recently as Program Support Assistant with the Springfield Vet Center.

On February 13, Mike, along with more than 1,000 other VA employees, were let go in one of the many rounds of firings we've witnessed under this administration.

When our servicemembers enter the service, we make them a promise: you protect us, and we‚Äôll take care of you. The VA is central to the obligation we have of fulfilling that promise, which is why we saw historic investments under President Biden with the enactment of the PACT Act. Now, this administration is turning their backs on our veterans at a time when they need our help the most.

The suggestion that nobody from the VA who interacts with veterans has been let go is simply not true, and Mike is a testament to that fact. The notion that we are going to cut programs like Medicaid and SNAP and terminate jobs with the VA, IRS, FAA, and other federal agencies all to support a tax cut for the top two percent is absurd.

That is why I am proud to host Mike as my guest for tonight's Presidential Address to Congress and share the stories of those that have been wrongfully terminated without cause.
